Complete, structured Core Java syllabus (exhaustive, version‑aware)
Below I group every major Core Java topic, then list subtopics and types you must master as a professional software engineer. Use this as a checklist for study, interview prep, or curriculum design.



1. Language Fundamentals
Lexical structure: tokens, identifiers, literals, comments, Unicode.

Types: primitive types; reference types; boxing/unboxing; type conversion.

Operators & control flow: expressions, statements, switch expressions, enhanced for.

Local‑variable type inference (var), text blocks.





2. Object Oriented Programming
Classes & objects, constructors, initialization blocks.

Inheritance, method overriding, super, this.

Polymorphism, dynamic dispatch.

Encapsulation, access modifiers, nested & inner classes.

Interfaces (default/static methods), functional interfaces, sealed classes.

3. Advanced Language Features (Java 9–26 era)
Modules (JPMS), module descriptors.

Records, pattern matching (instanceof, switch), sealed types.

Switch expressions, string templates, value objects (preview), structured concurrency (preview), virtual threads (Project Loom). 

4. Generics
Type parameters, wildcards (?, extends, super), type erasure, bounded types, generic methods, PECS.

5. Collections Framework
Interfaces: Collection, List, Set, Map, Queue, Deque.

Implementations: ArrayList, LinkedList, HashSet, TreeSet, HashMap, ConcurrentHashMap, CopyOnWriteArrayList.

Algorithms, iterators, spliterators, Collections utilities, concurrent collections.

6. Functional Programming & Streams
Lambda expressions, method references, FunctionalInterface.

Streams API: intermediate/terminal ops, parallel streams, collectors, Optional.

7. Concurrency & Parallelism
Threads, Runnable, Callable, thread lifecycle.

Executors, ScheduledExecutorService, ForkJoinPool.

Synchronization, volatile, synchronized, locks, atomics.

High‑level constructs: CountDownLatch, Semaphore, CyclicBarrier.

Memory Model (JMM), happens‑before rules.

Virtual threads & structured concurrency (modern features). 

8. I/O and Networking
java.io: streams, readers/writers, serialization (and alternatives).

java.nio: buffers, channels, selectors, file APIs.

Networking: Socket, ServerSocket, HttpClient (HTTP/2/3 support).

9. JVM Internals & Performance
Class loading, bytecode, class file format.

JIT compilation, HotSpot, GraalVM overview.

Garbage collection algorithms: Serial, Parallel, G1, ZGC, Shenandoah.

Profiling, benchmarking, memory tuning.

10. Standard Libraries & APIs
Date‑Time API (java.time), Locale, ResourceBundle.

Reflection, MethodHandle, InvokeDynamic.

Annotations, annotation processing (APT), javax.annotation.

Security: crypto APIs, keystore, TLS; Java 26 adds further crypto/AI enhancements. 

11. Interoperability & Tooling
JDBC, transactions, connection pooling.

JNI/JNA, JMX, serialization formats (JSON, XML), java.util.spi.

Build & packaging: javac, jlink, jpackage, Maven/Gradle integration.

REPL: JShell.

12. Testing, Best Practices, Patterns
Unit testing (JUnit), mocking, design patterns, clean code, secure coding, concurrency patterns.

How to use this list
Start with Language → OOP → Collections → Streams → Concurrency.

Practice with small projects that exercise JVM tuning, modules, and new features (records, virtual threads).

For production, target Java 25 LTS; evaluate Java 26 for new features and migration planning. 







****Complete, version‑aware Core Java micro‑topics list — exhaustive checklist for a senior software engineer in Chengalpattu, India (current time 27 Jun 2026 16:10 IST).** Java 26 shipped as a non‑LTS release on 17 Mar 2026 with multiple JEPs (structured concurrency, lazy constants, HTTP/3, primitive patterns, vector API, GC improvements). 

Language Fundamentals
Lexical and syntax: Unicode escapes; tokenization; comments; identifiers; literals (integer, floating, boolean, char, string, text blocks).





Types: primitives (byte, short, int, long, float, double, char, boolean); wrapper classes; boxing/unboxing; default values; type promotion & casting.

Variables and scope: local, instance, static, final, effectively final; local‑variable type inference (var); shadowing.

Operators and control flow: arithmetic, bitwise, relational, logical, ternary, assignment; if, switch (expressions & pattern switch), while, do, enhanced for, break/continue, labeled statements.





Object Oriented Programming
Classes and members: fields, methods, constructors, static initializers, instance initializers.

Access control: public, protected, private, package; module exports.

Inheritance and polymorphism: single inheritance, method overriding, covariant returns, super, this.

Nested types: static nested, inner, local, anonymous classes.

Interfaces and traits: abstract methods, default/static methods, private methods, functional interfaces, marker interfaces.

Immutability patterns: final fields, defensive copies, record semantics.





Generics and Type System
Generic declarations: class, interface, method, constructor generics.

Bounds: upper/lower bounds, multiple bounds, raw types.

Wildcards: ?, ? extends, ? super; PECS rule.

Type erasure: bridge methods, reified alternatives (VarHandles, MethodHandles).

Collections and Data Structures
Core interfaces: Collection, List, Set, Queue, Deque, Map, SortedSet, NavigableMap.

Implementations: ArrayList, LinkedList, HashSet, TreeSet, HashMap, TreeMap, LinkedHashMap, EnumMap, WeakHashMap.

Concurrent collections: ConcurrentHashMap, CopyOnWriteArrayList, BlockingQueue variants.

Iterators and Spliterators, Comparator, Collections utilities, memory/complexity tradeoffs.





Functional Programming and Streams
Lambda syntax and capture rules; method references.

Functional interfaces: Predicate, Function, Consumer, Supplier, UnaryOperator, BinaryOperator.

Streams API: creation, intermediate ops, terminal ops, short‑circuiting, collectors, custom collectors, parallel streams, Optional patterns.

Concurrency and Parallelism
Threads: lifecycle, daemon vs user, interruption.

Executors: ExecutorService, ScheduledExecutorService, ThreadPoolExecutor, ForkJoinPool.

Synchronization: synchronized, volatile, Lock, ReadWriteLock, StampedLock.

Atomics and concurrent utilities: Atomic*, CountDownLatch, CyclicBarrier, Semaphore, Phaser.

Memory Model: happens‑before, reordering, visibility, safe publication.

Modern features: virtual threads and structured concurrency (preview in recent JDKs). 





I O Networking and HTTP
java.io: Input/Output streams, Readers/Writers, serialization pitfalls.

java.nio: Buffers, Channels, Selectors, Files API, memory‑mapped files.

HTTP Client: java.net.http.HttpClient with HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 support in recent JDKs. 





JVM Internals and Performance
Class loading: bootstrap, platform, application loaders; linkage; classfile format.

Bytecode and invokedynamic, MethodHandle.

JIT and AOT, GraalVM overview.

Garbage collectors: Serial, Parallel, CMS (deprecated), G1, ZGC, Shenandoah; GC tuning and ergonomics. 





Libraries Tooling and Ecosystem
Date Time API (java.time), i18n, Locale.

Reflection and annotation processing, ServiceLoader.

Security: TLS, keystore, PEM encodings (recent JEPs). 

Build and packaging: javac, jlink, jpackage, Maven/Gradle, JShell.
